1 Section 1. Sections 1 to 5 of this act shall be known and may be
2 cited as the Foster Child Scholarships Act.
3 Sec. 2. For purposes of the Foster Child Scholarships Act:
4 (1) Department means the Department of Health and Human Services;
5 (2) Educational decisionmaker means a parent, guardian, foster care
6 parent, or other person with the authority to make educational decisions
7 for a child;
8 (3) Eligible student means any elementary or secondary school
9 student who was eligible to attend a public school in the preceding
10 semester or is starting school for the first time and is in foster care
11 or is the biological sibling of a foster child;
12 (4) Eligible school means any nongovernmental, privately operated
13 elementary or secondary school located in this state that (i) is operated
14 not for profit, (ii) complies with the antidiscrimination provisions of
15 42 U.S.C. 1981, as such section existed on January 1, 2025, (iii)
16 complies with all health and safety laws or codes that apply to privately
17 operated schools, and (iv) fulfills the applicable accreditation or
18 approval requirements established by the State Board of Education
19 pursuant to section 79-318; and
20 (5) HOPE Scholarship means a financial grant-in-aid to be used to
21 pay all or part of the cost to educate an eligible student attending an
22 eligible school.
23 Sec. 3. (1) The department shall establish the Foster Child
24 Scholarship Program to provide HOPE Scholarships to eligible students to
25 pay the costs associated with attending an eligible school beginning with
26 the 2025-26 school year.
27 (2)(a) An educational decisionmaker of an eligible student shall
28 qualify for a HOPE Scholarship for a foster child to enroll in and attend
29 an eligible school, upon being accepted for admission at a participating
30 school.
31 (b) An eligible student shall retain program eligibility regardless
